Our main research question will be: Do returns to educational attainment differ by college major?

Step 1: Observe the Data

Q01: Take a look at the ipums dataset. Describe its structure in words.

  • How many observations are there? This data has 100,000 observations of individuals.

  • Is it cross-sectional, time-series, or panel data? It is cross-sectional. There are no years. Who/what does each observation (row) describe? It describes an individuals location (state), their age, total income, their years of schooling, and what degree they received (if any).

  • What qualitative information is contained in this dataset? Their degree type, degree level, and state.

  • What quantitative information is contained in this dataset? Their age, income, and years of education.

Q06: Create a new variable for log incomes instead. How does the shape of the distribution change?

# Write your code here
ipums_tbl %>%

Step 3: Analyze the Data

Q09: Regress your transformation of the income variable on school attainment. Report and interpret your estimates in the context of the returns to education 

# Write your code here
ipums_tbl %>%
  filter(INCTOT > 0) %>%
  lm(log(INCTOT) ~ school, data = .) %>%
  broom::tidy()
## # A tibble: 2  5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)    8.54    0.0200      427.        0
## 2 school         0.137   0.00144      95.0       0

The regression suggests that an additional year of education is associated with a 13.7% increase in income.

Q10: Does there seem to be any evidence of heteroskedasticity in this relationship? Plot the residuals from your previous regression at different levels of school attendance and interpret. 

# Write your code here
model <- ipums_tbl %>%
  filter(INCTOT > 0) %>%
  lm(log(INCTOT) ~ school, data = .)

ipums_tbl <- ipums_tbl %>%
  filter(INCTOT > 0) %>%
  mutate(residuals = residuals(model))

ggplot(ipums_tbl, aes(x = school, y = residuals)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

There does not seem to be any evidence of heteroskedasticity. We can see this because there is no systemic variation in the residuals as years of school increases. The linear fit line also seems to be flat around 0.

Q11: What are some potential omitted variables in the relationship between school attainment and income which could bias your regression estimates?

  • How might these variable be related to both income and school attainment?

State of residence and sex may be possible omitted variables. State is potentially related to income as different states will have different economies (and employment opportunities). Each state may also have different quality of educational institutions which affect future labor market outcomes. Sex may also be related to income due to possible sex-based discrimination in income and to school attainment as there may be differential trends in school attainment by sex.

  • Choose one variable and argue which direction (positive or negative) of bias likely would result from omitting that variable.

For state of residence: If a state has a stronger economy (California vs Arkansas), then income and state would be positively correlated. This would bias the estimate upwards.

Step 4: Discuss your conclusions

Q14: In this dataset, does it seem like some degrees have better returns to lifetime income than others?

  • Make sure to cite your estimate results and explain why they support your claim.

Yes. Above I ran a regression for social sciences, engineering and economics. For these degree categories, social science has an interacted effect of 0.02299027, engineering of 0.03733596 and economics of 0.03556361. Which suggest that each individual major has different returns to total income as the coefficient in the interaction are different.

Q15: What are some reasons why your estimates may not be enough to answer the question of whether degree type actually has a causal effect on the returns to education?

There are so many other potential factors that determine wages, such as sex mentioned before. The fundamental problem of causal inference means that we cannot observe how someone that studied economics would have done if they had studied engineering. So we cannot directly compare them. However, we are also likely missing many other factors which get absorbed in the error term of the model, like institutional quality or labor market conditions. Lastly, this is also a cross-sectional dataset. We cannot observe trends in any way, but rather the snapshot of how these individuals are.
